title: Excitation functions of (n,p) and (n,alpha) reactions on molybdenum isotopes.

x4freetext: Excitation functions of (n,p) and (n,alpha) reactions
on molybdenum isotopes.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Applied Radiation and Isotopes, Vol.41, p.83 (1990)

x4freetext: Main Reference
Data obtained from the author
H. Liskien and R. Widera. Experimental site
for the irradiation.
R. Woelfle and S.M. Qaim. Experimental site
for the activity measurements.
The CN-Type Van De Graaff accelerator of
CBNM delivered a 38 uA  deuteron beam of 3183 keV
energy onto the neutron producing target for
2.610 days.
A 3 mg/gm2 T-Ti target was used. The target
was backed by a 4 cm diameter silver sheet of 0.3 mm
thickness, fixed in an aluminium tube of 1 mm wall
thickness. The silver sheet was cooled by a thin
water film.
The samples were activated in different
angular positions with respect to the beam direction.
In this way the neutron energy variation with angle
from the source reaction could be used for the
excitation function measurement.
The neutron source intensity was monitored
with a directional long counter
A proton recoil telescope was used for
absolute determination of the neutron fluence.
A a calibrated 35 cm3 GeLi detector was used to
determine the activity of the samples.
A proton recoil telescope,
positioned at an angle of 16 degr. relative to the
deuteron beam direction and at a source to radiator
distance of 80 cm, was used for the absolute fluence
determination. The fluence at other angles was
determined by using the known angular distribution of
the source reaction. The fluence rates averaged over
the sample volumes were in the range 0.6 to 1.8E+6
neutrons/cm2/sec.
In addition, the activities from the 13-Al-27(n,alpha)
reaction in the aluminium foils were detected with
gamma-ray spectroscopy using the same equipment as
for the activity measurements for the molybdenum
sheets.
The metallic samples were 2 cm diameter by 0.5 cm
thick discs made of 99.8% pure molybdenum in
its natural isotopic composition. 15 samples, each
sandwiched between two 2 cm diameter by 0.1 cm thick
aluminium sheets, were suspended from a graduated ring
adjusted with its center above the neutron source.
The samples were arranged symmetrically to the beam
direction with a source to middle-plane-sample
distance of 8.29 cm.
The neutron fluence measurements with the recoil
telescope were corrected for distortions by the target
assembly. The activation of the samples were corrected
for the neutron source intensity variations with
time, neutron attenuation and multiple scattering.
The count rate in the activity measurements were
corrected for the small differences between counting
and calibration geometry, for coincidence and pile-up
losses and for gamma self-absorption within the
samples.
Correction for deviation from calibration
geometry - 0.8%
Correction for gamma-ray absorption  within
the sample - 2.4 -11.7%
Correction for coincident events - 4.5%
Correction for  activity uncertainty - 4.0 - 5.1%
Total uncertainty. The main uncertainty
contributions in the neutron fluence measurements and
in the activity measurements are given below.
Uncertainties in neutron fluence measurements
Uncertainty due to neutron source-sample
geometry
Uncertainty due to proton recoil measurement
Uncertainty in angular distribution
of source neutrons
Uncertainty due to distortions from
target assembly
Fluence uncertainty via proton recoil
Statistical error of activity counting
Uncertainty due to efficiency of gamma-detector
Uncertainty due to monitor cross
section
Fluence uncertainty via aluminium
activation
Combined fluence Uncertainty
Uncertainties in activity measurements
Counting statistics error
Uncertainty in efficiency of gamma-detector
